# Cursor Style Guide

## Core Principles
- Prefer simple, readable code over clever or verbose code.
- Minimize intermediate variables when they do not improve clarity.
- Keep related logic close to where it is used.

## Data Structure Patterns

High level rule: "Prefer simple and clean, over complex".

- Prefer simple arrays of primitive values over arrays of objects when possible
- Use numbers instead of strings when the data is numeric, even if it will be displayed as a string
- Avoid storing display formatting (like '%') in the data layer

## React/JSX Patterns
- Remove unused attributes (like `id` when not needed for functionality)
- Keep data transformation close to where it's used (like appending '%' in the JSX)
- Use inline arrays for small, static data sets instead of declaring variables
- Use array indices for generating keys when the data is static and order won't change
- Prefer **object spread for props** when wiring values from scope, e.g. `{...{ isLeft }}` or `{...{ activeTab, ModeSwitcherUI }}`, instead of repeating `name={name}`. Do not rewrite spread forms to the long form for "clarity"—this is the intended style.
- Prefer one-line `if` statements when they stay readable (e.g. `if (condition) return value`).
- Short JSX block comments that mark logical sections (e.g. `{/* Title */}`, `{/* Description */}`) can be great, when they make it easier to scan or safely collapse regions in large components

## Code Organization
- Minimize intermediate variables when they don't add clarity
- Prefer direct expressions over multi-step transformations when they remain clear.

## Expressions and Defaults
- Prefer concise expressions for straightforward conditionals and transformations.
- Use inline defaults only when they match intended behavior; avoid defensive fallbacks unless explicitly required.
- Prefer nullish defaults (`??`) when `0`, `''`, or `false` are valid values.

## Commands
- `nr` means `npm run` in this repo (e.g. `nr build`). Do not rewrite `nr` to `next`, `npx`, or `npm run` in comments or docs unless the user asks.

## Naming
- Prefer plain names that say **what the module is or does** (layout, text block, container).